Clustering of differentially expressed genes (RNAseq)

last changed: 2023-08-29

Hierarchical Clustering

Load the rlog transformed DESeq data set and construct the required data frames. The function assay returns the values and colData returns the information about the experimental design.

> rlog.heat <- readRDS(file = "./../Significance_testing/Data/rlog_RNAseq_sig.rds")
> head(rlog.heat)
## class: DESeqTransform 
## dim: 6 9 
## metadata(1): version
## assays(1): ''
## rownames(6): ENSG00000187961 ENSG00000187583 ... ENSG00000158286
##   ENSG00000049249
## rowData names(7): baseMean baseVar ... dispFit rlogIntercept
## colnames(9): Exp1_0h Exp1_05h ... Exp1_4h Exp2_4h
## colData names(6): ID name ... Time sizeFactor
> m.RNAseq <- assay(rlog.heat)
> head(m.RNAseq)

> info.RNAseq <- data.frame(colData(rlog.heat))
> paged_table(info.RNAseq)

Next this data can be used to perform hierarchical clustering, which is implemented in pheatmap. colorRampPallette was used to change the annotation color.

> col <- colorRampPalette(rev(brewer.pal(n = 7, name = "RdBu")))(100)
> 
> heat.hieracial <- pheatmap(m.RNAseq, 
+                   cluster_cols = F, 
+                   show_rownames = F, 
+                   scale = "row", 
+                   color = col,
+                   annotation_col = data.frame(time = info.RNAseq[, "Time"], 
+                                               row.names = rownames(info.RNAseq)))

Kmeans Clustering

To get a better separation of the data, kmeans clustering was performed. For this, the data was scaled to Z-scores using the function scale.

> norm.m.RNAseq <- t(scale(t(m.RNAseq)))

Next, kmeans was used to perform the clustering and a factor indicating the clusters was added to each of the scaled matrices. The clustering for centers = 5 (5 cluster) yielded the best result, as more clusters divided data with a similar course.

> clus.kmeans <- kmeans(norm.m.RNAseq, 4)
> lapply(clus.kmeans, head)

> saveRDS(clus.kmeans, "./Data/kmeans.rds")
> 
> m.kmeans <- cbind(norm.m.RNAseq, cluster = as.factor(clus.kmeans$cluster))
> m.kmeans <- m.kmeans[order(m.kmeans[, "cluster"]), ]

To visualize the clustering a heatmap was plotted using pheatmap. The functions colorRampPalette and brewer.pal were used to generate the color for the annotations and Z-values, respectively.

> col <- colorRampPalette(rev(brewer.pal(n = 7, name = "RdBu")))(100)
> col2 <- brewer.pal(n = 8, name = "Dark2")
> clus.col <- c("1" = col2[1], "2" = col2[2], "3" = col2[3], "4" = col2[4])
> ann.col2 <- list(cluster = clus.col[1:4])
> 
> heat.kmeans.RNAseq <- pheatmap(m.kmeans[ ,-ncol(m.kmeans)],
+                               cluster_rows = F,
+                               cluster_cols = F,
+                               show_rownames = F, 
+                               color = col,
+                               annotation_col = data.frame(time = info.RNAseq[, "Time"], row.names = rownames(info.RNAseq)),
+                               annotation_row = data.frame(cluster = as.factor(m.kmeans[, "cluster"])),
+                               annotation_colors = ann.col2,
+                               main = "Gene expression")

Lastly, the cluster centroids (Z-scores) were plotted separately to visualize the change in H3K27ac over time between the two constructs.

> kmeans <- melt(clus.kmeans$centers)
> ind <- match(kmeans$Var2, rownames(info.RNAseq))
> data.kmeans <- cbind(kmeans, info.RNAseq[ind, "Time"])
> colnames(data.kmeans) <- c("cluster", "name", "Z_score", "time")
> paged_table(data.kmeans)
> ggplot(data.kmeans) + 
+     geom_point(aes(x = time, y = Z_score), size = 1) +
+     stat_summary(aes(x = time, y = Z_score), fun = mean, geom = "line", linewidth = 1) +
+     facet_grid(rows = data.kmeans$cluster) +
+     theme_bw() +
+     labs(title = "Cluster centroids", y = "z-scores")
